<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,1672,1878]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1672,1698]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Remarks</emphasis>
. A fair number of the specimens examined from Fannin County have faint to distinct dark maculation on their elytra, but otherwise the elytral color of the examined 
<collectingRegion box="[899,964,1708,1734]" country="United States of America" name="Texas" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Texas</collectingRegion>
material is pale. The finely and uniformly denticulate ridge on the margins of ventrites III–V and the shape of the median lobe are the important diagnostic characters separating this species from all other species of similar size and coloration.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,1672,1878]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,447,1815,1842]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Specimens examined</emphasis>
. See Appendix 4. The genitalia of 
<specimenCount box="[836,936,1815,1842]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="male">15 males</specimenCount>
from 10 
<collectingRegion box="[1039,1104,1816,1842]" country="United States of America" name="Texas" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Texas</collectingRegion>
localities were examined and from many additional specimens not from 
<collectingRegion box="[628,697,1852,1878]" country="United States of America" name="Texas" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Texas</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
